Text Analysis in R for Data Analytics | Big Data

Maastricht University

04/10/2020

In this document we show you how to use Natural Language Processing (NLP) for big data text analysis. First we will load some Tweets from Twitter as a Corpus, which is our textual dataset. Before we can analysise it we first need to clean the data, for example, by removing any stop words, such as the, or and, or if. For this we need the packages: twitterR, and a text mining package tm. The document then shows two quick examples of text analysis techniques for a small sample of big data; firstly we create a Wordcloud and secondly we analyse the sentiment that individuals have towards the issue being tweeted about. For this we use two additional packages: wordcloud and syuzhet, so make sure that you have first installed them for the R syntax to run correctly. To plot the sentiment analysis on a graph we have chosen to use the ggplot2 format, so make sure that this package is already installed.

Load Data

The first step is to upload the data into the R environment. Pay attention to the working directory that you are using. Change working directory if required and load the new packages for twitter and text mining.

library(twitteR)
library(tm)

Loading Text Data: Create corpus database

tweets.text <- readChar("greenbonds.txt", nchars=file.info("greenbonds.txt")$size)
tweets.text.corpus <- Corpus(VectorSource(tweets.text))

Text Cleaning: remove stop words

tweets.text.corpus <- tm_map(tweets.text.corpus,
function(x)removeWords(x,stopwords()))

Wordcloud

library("wordcloud")
wordcloud(tweets.text.corpus,min.freq = 2, scale=c(7,0.5),
colors=brewer.pal(8, "Dark2"),  
random.color= TRUE, random.order = FALSE, max.words = 150)

Sentiment Analysis

The sentiment analysis is conducted to create a visualization. Here we need to transpose the data to a dataframe and compute the column sum across the rows for each type of grouping variable.

library(syuzhet)
tweets.text <- iconv(tweets.text,"WINDOWS-1252","UTF-8") #International keyboards
sentiment <- get_nrc_sentiment(tweets.text)
sentiment_df <- data.frame(t(sentiment))
sentiment_df1 <- data.frame(rowSums(sentiment_df))

# name rows and columns of the dataframe
names(sentiment_df1)[1] <- "count"
sentiment_df1 <- cbind("sentiment" = rownames(sentiment_df1), 
sentiment_df1)
rownames(sentiment_df1) <- NULL

Plot the distinct emotions:

library(ggplot2)
qplot(sentiment, data=sentiment_df1[1:8,], weight=count,
geom="bar",fill=sentiment)+ggtitle("Sentiment Analysis")

To plot only the positive and negative emotions, which are the final two rows:

qplot(sentiment, data=sentiment_df1[9:10,], weight=count,
geom="bar",fill=sentiment)+ggtitle("Sentiment Analysis on Green Bond Tweets")
